A new science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to think about the need for a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
Most scientists assume that the fundamental questions of science have been answered.
Regarding the major challenges, people believe that there is only little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the great unresolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and third, problems whose solution relies on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be utilizing already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
The models of today do work.
However, a growing group of scientists points out phenomena that are not easily explained by today's theories.
These problems do occur more frequently, but they are also skillfully circumvented because the science to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is relatively well-established.
Physics, at least the part with which we as ordinary people are confronted, is well-researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry are also on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it can be assumed that the fundamental mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Furthermore, there are the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely undisputed.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the integration of several disciplines.
For example, consider the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules, whose interaction occurs on the principles of physics. The information transmitted in the process is transferred due to the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate and transfer information through the exchange of chemical substances.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: here, information is exchanged through language, signs, and thoughts.
At each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes at each level.
However, information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even attempt to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this lack, some scientists have tried to redefine the tools for explaining processes within a level in order to apply them to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes, this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the underlying problem is not solved: How is the information exchanged between individual levels composed, and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary researchers who gathered in Paris has loosely formed itself under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and disciplines and have been working together in a decentralized manner for eight years.
In addition to scientists from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discussion.
Most of the group is using this "transplantation strategy," where the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented to another level.
Others, however, believe that a completely new approach is necessary.
Many scientific norms, in their view, are the product of historical accidents, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, similar to their counterparts in the business world, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries need to build similar resources to those of industrialized countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the large institutions.
The most thoughtful approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computer capacity at every corner.
The most brilliant and, in the truest sense of the word, world-changing insights in the field of physics over the past decades did not come, as expected, from the known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has helped cognitive scientists gain important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") now come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements went down in history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, the identity of space and time changed. The FIS conference in July was the unexpected beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps that require explanations were identified.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group to then identify those problems that could be solved if this new science is ever developed, or discovered, if you will.

